'''Peter van Diest''' ([[Latin]]ised as '''Petrus Diesthemius''') was a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] writer from the [[Low Countries]]. The late-15th-century [[morality play]] ''[[Elckerlijc]]'' is attributed to him.

''Elckerlijc'', which was translated into English to become the famous ''[[Everyman (play)|Everyman]]'', has come down to us in manuscripts that fail to mention the play's author. A 1539 [[Latin]] translation by [[Georgius Macropedius]], however, states that its original author is one Petrus Diesthemius ('Peter of Diest'). Little else is known of this writer; he has been identified with the [[Carthusian]] monk [[Petrus Dorlandus]] (1454&ndash;1507), who lived in [[Diest]] (in present-day [[Belgium]]) and wrote [[Hagiography|lives of the saints]]. This identification, however, is controversial among [[philologist]]s.


